UNDIAGNOSED POSTPARTUM INFECTION - INDIA: (PB) FATAL, SCRUB TYPHUS SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 2 Aug 2021 02:29 PM IST
Source: The Tribune [edited]
https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/patiala/clueless-about-infection-say-doctors-at-city-hospital-292236


Mystery shrouds post-operative complications of women after delivery at the Gynaecology Department of Mata Kaushalya Hospital [located in Patiala, Punjab, India]. One such case is of a 25 year old woman, who lost her life during treatment at the Government Rajindra Hospital [Patiala] after she was referred from the Government Mata Kaushalya Hospital [Patiala].

Last week [week of 26 Jul 2021], a woman with similar symptoms was referred to the PGIMER, Chandigarh [Postgraduate Institute of Medical Education and Research (PGIMER) is a public tertiary care university hospital in Chandigarh (capital of Punjab and Haryana), which caters to patients from all over Punjab, Jammu and Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, and Haryana (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jammu_and_Kashmir_(union_territory)) - Mod.ML]. A health condition of anuria, wherein kidneys stop producing urine, is continually being reported in post-delivery cases of young women.

Sources informed that around 5 cases with similar symptoms had already been reported within 15 days. After the unusual postoperative complications, the department had to shut the operation theatre (OT) for 72 hours last week. To mitigate the source of infection, insecticide was sprayed in the labour room, ward, and the OT.

The hospital authorities also checked laundry, drugs, and other things at the department. However, they were still clueless about how the infection was spreading. Dr Aarti Pandove, senior medical officer, Mata Kaushalya Hospital, said, "We have been trying our best to identify the problem. We have already checked everything. However, we have not been able to identify reasons so far." Dr Pandove further said that they were in contact with the PGIMER, Chandigarh, in this regard.

Two of the 5 women, who showed similar symptoms, were found positive for scrub typhus, the sources added. Scrub typhus, known as bush typhus, is a disease caused by bacteria called _Orientia tsutsugamushi_. It spreads among people through bites of infected chiggers (larval mites). However, the hospital authorities claimed that only one patient was found positive for scrub typhus.

Meanwhile, a health official said, "An inquiry should be conducted into the death of a woman and other cases to avoid any further loss of life in the future."

[byline: Karam Prakash]

